<BlogLayout
  title="Prusa Is Sending Their Flagship Machine. Here's Why That Matters."
  description="The Prusa CORE One L is coming to 3D3D. A bigger build volume, enclosed chamber, and serious capabilities that unlock new kinds of fabrication work."
  datePublished="2025-08-18"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>The Call</h2>

  <p>
    When Prusa announced the CORE One L, I paid attention. When they told me one was coming to 3D3D, I cleared space in the shop. This isn't just another printer, it's the machine that changes what we can say yes to.
  </p>

  <p>
    The CORE One was already a solid machine. Fully enclosed, CoreXY motion system, active chamber heating, input shaping. The L version scales all of that up with a build volume that lets us print parts we've been turning down for a year.
  </p>

  <h2>What Bigger Actually Means</h2>

  <p>
    Build volume isn't just a spec sheet number. It directly determines what you can manufacture in one piece versus what you have to print in sections and join. Joined parts are always weaker than monolithic parts. Every seam is a potential failure point, especially in marine and automotive applications where vibration wants to find every weakness.
  </p>

  <p>
    With the CORE One L, I can print full-size dashboard panels, large marine brackets, complete intake manifold prototypes, and enclosure housings that previously required splitting into three or four pieces. One print, one part, no seams.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Marine:</strong> Full instrument panel covers, large ventilation housings, complete hatch frames.</li>
    <li><strong>Automotive:</strong> Air intake ducts, dashboard components, fender-mounted brackets.</li>
    <li><strong>Industrial:</strong> Equipment housings, large jigs and fixtures, prototype enclosures.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Enclosed Chamber Changes Materials</h2>

  <p>
    Active chamber heating is the real story here. When you can maintain 60-70C ambient inside the print chamber, the range of materials you can reliably print expands dramatically. ABS and ASA print without warping drama. Nylon composites behave predictably. Even some of the exotic engineering polymers become feasible.
  </p>

  <p>
    I've been wanting to push further into PPA and high-temp nylons for engine bay applications. The chamber control on the CORE One L makes that realistic. Consistent chamber temperature means consistent parts, which means I can guarantee results to clients instead of hoping for them.
  </p>

  <h2>CoreXY Speed</h2>

  <p>
    The CoreXY motion system with input shaping means this machine is fast without sacrificing print quality. For production work, speed is money. A part that took 14 hours on an i3-style printer might print in 8 on the CORE One L. That's not just time saved, it's more capacity, more orders fulfilled, faster turnaround for clients.
  </p>

  <p>
    Speed matters most when we're doing field deployment or event work. Printing a part on-site while a client watches, you want it done in hours, not overnight. The CORE One L makes that possible for larger parts.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Prusa Sending It Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Prusa doesn't send machines to just anyone. The fact that they're putting their flagship in our shop says something about what 3D3D is building. We're not a hobby operation, we're a fabrication company pushing these machines into real applications: offshore sailing, motorsport, industrial repair, field deployment.
  </p>

  <p>
    That relationship with Prusa is important to us. They make the tools, we push the tools to their limits and report back. It's a partnership built on actually using the equipment in demanding environments, not just reviewing it on YouTube.
  </p>

  <h2>What This Means for Clients</h2>

  <p>
    If you've contacted us before and we had to say "that part's too big for our build volume", call back. The CORE One L removes that constraint for most applications. Bigger parts, better materials, faster turnaround. The shop is about to level up.
  </p>
</BlogLayout>
